  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. These laws operate through international cooperation and the establishment of common standards for national legislation. Here's a breakdown of some of the key instruments:\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force on Money Laundering (FATF):** While not a law itself, the FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. Its **40 Recommendations** are the globally recognized standard for AML/CFT measures. Many countries implement these recommendations into their national laws.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the earliest international efforts to criminalize money laundering related to drug trafficking. It requires countries to establish money laundering as a criminal offense and to confiscate the proceeds of drug crimes.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to cover proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes. It also promotes international cooperation in investigation, prosecution, and extradition.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003):** This convention addresses money laundering related to",
